    },
    {
      "id": "3b11e6744c333812c82cc4ca2b45c162332f3a27",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-12-02 06:02:12.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nUsing \"%g\" will drop trailing decimal places if they are zero. If you have a limit that is exactly 1TB then it will print \"1T\". If it is 1.52TB it should print 1.52T.  Not sure why that isn't working, maybe I got the precision wrong, try \"%4.2g\" to see if that makes a difference?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "3b1525385754152316020ebabf4f999357efa913",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 104,
        "name": "Niu Yawei",
        "email": "yawei.niu@intel.com",
        "username": "niu",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-12-02 09:29:28.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "81644d06ddd1fa3ca008ce849652c778a3374912",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-12-05 11:01:29.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nIt looks like \"%5.4g\" will work:\n\n int main(int argc, char *argv[])\n {\n\tprintf(\"%4.4g\\n\", (double)10.444);\n\tprintf(\"%5.4g\\n\", (double)110.444);\n\tprintf(\"%5.4g\\n\", (double)1030.444);\n }\n\nprints out:\n\n 10.44\n 110.4\n  1030",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "2e626029f437567e7b2124c910cf40cee1b0ff1f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 104,
        "name": "Niu Yawei",
        "email": "yawei.niu@intel.com",
        "username": "niu",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-12-16 07:22:08.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nIt looks like \"%5.4g\" will work:\n int main(int argc, char *argv[])\n {\n\tprintf(\"%4.4g\\n\", (double)10.444);\n\tprintf(\"%5.4g\\n\", (double)110.444);\n\tprintf(\"%5.4g\\n\", (double)1030.444);\n }\nprints out:\n 10.44\n 110.4\n  1030\n\nAndreas, I think what we want are: 1.4, 10.4 , 110.4 and 1030.4.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "923ffdecd523b22064e1390d2306e4bae5d5874d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-12-16 08:20:06.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nNiu, I think it makes sense to have a limited significant digits for larger numbers, so I think \"%5.4g\" is just right:\n\n int main(int argc, char *argv[])\n {\n\tprintf(\"%5.4g\\n\", (double)1.4404);\n \tprintf(\"%5.4g\\n\", (double)10.444);\n\tprintf(\"%5.4g\\n\", (double)710.444);\n\tprintf(\"%5.4g\\n\", (double)1030.444);\n }\n\nGives:\n\n  1.44\n 10.44\n 710.4\n  1030\n\nWhich I think is just right, and avoids adding complexity to the code.  This can be used to print values between 1.0 and 1024 MB/GB/TB easily.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
